    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>AIDS in Central Asia</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lauren Galli letter comments favorably on October 16 article on needle-sharing program for heroin addicts in Bishkek, Kyrgyzstan, which is aimed at stopping spread of AIDS</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Heroin and Needles: Battling AIDS in Central Asia'' (Bishkek Journal, Oct. 16):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Heroin and Needles: Battling AIDS in Central Asia'' (Bishkek Journal, Oct. 16):</p>
        <p>I was shocked that needle exchanges had been opened in Bishkek and Osh, Kyrgyzstan, to deal with the growing drug problem in the region. Yet as I read further, my views changed. I believe that this is a satisfactory temporary solution to stop the spread of the AIDS virus. Anything that can decrease the number of AIDS cases in the world is a positive solution. Yet what is Central Asia doing to stop heroin use?</p>
        <p>LAUREN GALLI  Boston, Oct. 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
